    stem: "A 55-year-old female with severe hypertension (BP 210/120 mmHg), acute aortic dissection (Stanford type B), and HR 110 bpm arrives at the ED. The NP must initiate IV esmolol before any vasodilator. What is the pharmacological rationale for beta-blocker FIRST in aortic dissection, and why would starting nitroprusside alone be dangerous?",
    optionA: "Esmolol is given first because it directly repairs the aortic intimal tear; nitroprusside has no anti-dissection properties",
