    optionC: "Esmolol prevents arrhythmias that commonly occur during dissection; nitroprusside alone causes fatal methemoglobinemia within minutes",
    optionD: "Esmolol is given first simply because its IV onset is faster than nitroprusside; there is no specific pharmacological rationale for the sequence",
    correctAnswer: "B",
    rationale: "AORTIC DISSECTION HEMODYNAMIC TARGETS: The two forces propagating dissection: (1) ABSOLUTE BLOOD PRESSURE: Higher pressure → more force on the intimal flap → propagation. (2) dP/dt (rate of left ventricular pressure rise): How RAPIDLY pressure is generated during systole. Even at the same BP, a faster/stronger contraction creates more SHEAR STRESS on the aortic wall → more dangerous for the dissection flap. Target: SBP <120 mmHg AND HR <60 bpm. ESMOLOL: Ultra-short-acting β1-selective blocker (t½ = 9 minutes, hydrolyzed by RBC esterases). IV bolus + infusion → immediately reduces: (a) HR → less pulsatile stress, (b) Contractility → weaker systolic ejection, (c) dP/dt → reduced shear force on aortic wall. WHY NOT NITROPRUSSIDE FIRST: Sodium nitroprusside → spontaneous release of NO → activates guanylyl cyclase → cGMP → vascular smooth muscle relaxation → rapid arterial vasodilation → BP drops. However: sudden BP drop → baroreceptors detect hypotension → REFLEX SYMPATHETIC ACTIVATION → catecholamine surge → increased HR + contractility → INCREASED dP/dt → WORSE shear stress on dissection flap → propagation extension. This is why beta-blocker FIRST is a cardinal rule: (1) Esmolol controls HR + dP/dt. (2) THEN add nitroprusside for additional BP reduction without reflex tachycardia (beta-blocker blunts the reflex). Alternative to nitroprusside: clevidipine or nicardipine (IV dihydropyridine CCBs) — less reflex tachycardia. Labetalol alone (alpha-1 + beta blockade) can address both HR and BP simultaneously.",
    explanationA: "No pharmacological agent 'repairs' the intimal tear. Medical management targets HEMODYNAMIC forces (BP + dP/dt) to prevent propagation. Surgical/endovascular repair addresses the tear itself.",
    explanationB: "Correct. Dissection propagation depends on BP + dP/dt. Esmolol reduces both. Nitroprusside alone lowers BP BUT triggers reflex tachycardia → increased dP/dt → increased shear stress → potential propagation. Beta-blocker first eliminates this reflex.",
    explanationC: "While arrhythmias can occur in dissection, that is not the primary rationale. Methemoglobinemia from nitroprusside occurs with PROLONGED infusion (cyanide/thiocyanate toxicity), not within minutes. The danger is reflex tachycardia increasing dP/dt.",
    explanationD: "The sequence has CRITICAL pharmacological rationale: dP/dt control must precede vasodilation to prevent reflex tachycardia. This is not about onset speed (both are rapid IV agents).",
    examTip: "Aortic dissection anti-impulse therapy: (1) IV beta-blocker FIRST: Esmolol (titratable, ultra-short t½) or labetalol (dual alpha+beta). Target HR <60 bpm. (2) THEN add vasodilator if SBP >120: Nitroprusside, clevidipine, or nicardipine. NEVER vasodilator without beta-blockade. Esmolol advantage: 9-minute half-life → rapidly titratable, stops quickly if complications arise. Nitroprusside toxicity with prolonged use: cyanide accumulation → lactic acidosis (treat with sodium thiosulfate + hydroxocobalamin).",
