    rationale: "PAH PATHOBIOLOGY — THREE PATHWAYS: PAH involves dysfunction in three key vascular pathways: (1) ENDOTHELIN PATHWAY: Endothelin-1 (ET-1) is a potent vasoconstrictor and mitogen overproduced in PAH. Acts via ETA receptors (vasoconstriction, proliferation on VSMC) and ETB receptors (mixed: ET clearance + NO release on endothelium, but vasoconstriction on VSMC). Ambrisentan selectively blocks ETA → reduces vasoconstriction + proliferation while preserving ETB-mediated ET-1 clearance. Bosentan blocks both ETA + ETB (non-selective). (2) NO-cGMP PATHWAY: Endothelial NO → activates soluble guanylyl cyclase (sGC) → cGMP → PKG → vasodilation + antiproliferation. In PAH, NO production is DEFICIENT + PDE5 (which degrades cGMP) is OVEREXPRESSED in pulmonary vasculature → net cGMP deficit → vasoconstriction. Tadalafil inhibits PDE5 → prevents cGMP breakdown → amplifies whatever NO signal exists → vasodilation. (PDE5 is concentrated in pulmonary vasculature → relative selectivity.) (3) PROSTACYCLIN PATHWAY: Endothelial PGI2 (prostacyclin) → IP receptor → cAMP → vasodilation + antiplatelet. In PAH, prostacyclin synthase is deficient. Treated by: epoprostenol (IV PGI2), treprostinil (SC/IV/inhaled), selexipag (oral IP receptor agonist). COMBINATION RATIONALE: Each pathway is independently dysfunctional → targeting multiple pathways simultaneously produces additive/synergistic benefit. AMBITION TRIAL: Upfront combination (ambrisentan + tadalafil) vs monotherapy → 50% reduction in clinical failure events (death, hospitalization, disease progression). Now standard of care for intermediate/high-risk PAH.",
