    correctAnswer: "A",
    rationale: "MECHANICAL VALVE THROMBOGENICITY: Mechanical prosthetic valves (bileaflet, tilting disc) expose ARTIFICIAL SURFACES (pyrolytic carbon, titanium, polyester sewing ring) to flowing blood. These surfaces trigger: (1) CONTACT ACTIVATION PATHWAY: Factor XII contacts the artificial surface → autoactivation → XIIa activates XI → IXa → factor Xa → thrombin generation. This is the INTRINSIC pathway — heavily involved in foreign-body-triggered coagulation. (2) TISSUE FACTOR PATHWAY: Surgical disruption of endothelium + chronic inflammation at sewing ring → tissue factor exposure → extrinsic pathway activation. (3) PLATELET ACTIVATION: Artificial surfaces lack endothelial antithrombogenic properties (no NO, no PGI2, no thrombomodulin) → immediate platelet adhesion → GPIIb/IIIa-mediated aggregation. (4) FLOW DISRUPTION: Mechanical valves create areas of stasis and turbulence → blood coagulates in low-flow zones. WHY WARFARIN WORKS: Warfarin depletes vitamin K-dependent factors → reduces Factors II, VII, IX, X → inhibits BOTH pathways simultaneously. (1) Factor IX reduction → suppresses intrinsic/contact pathway (critical for artificial surface-triggered coagulation). (2) Factor VII reduction → suppresses extrinsic/tissue factor pathway. (3) Factor II (thrombin) reduction → suppresses the final common amplification step. (4) Factor X → suppresses the convergence point. This MULTI-FACTOR suppression provides sufficient anticoagulation for the intense thrombogenicity of mechanical surfaces. WHY DOACs FAIL: Dabigatran (direct thrombin inhibitor) → blocks only Factor IIa. Does NOT reduce Factor IX (critical for contact pathway) or Factor VII (extrinsic pathway). The single-factor approach is INSUFFICIENT. RE-ALIGN TRIAL: Randomized 252 patients, dabigatran vs warfarin in mechanical valves. STOPPED EARLY: dabigatran group had MORE thromboembolic events (9% vs 0% valve thrombosis/stroke) AND more bleeding (27% vs 12%). This was a definitive negative trial.",
    explanationA: "Correct. Mechanical valve thrombosis heavily involves the contact activation (intrinsic) pathway + tissue factor pathway → requires MULTI-FACTOR suppression (warfarin: II, VII, IX, X). Single-factor DOACs are insufficient → RE-ALIGN proved this with increased thrombosis AND bleeding.",
    explanationB: "Cost is not the reason. DOACs were proven HARMFUL in mechanical valve patients (RE-ALIGN trial). This is about pharmacological inadequacy of single-factor inhibition against artificial surface-triggered coagulation.",
