    rationale: "PRIMARY ALDOSTERONISM: Most common CURABLE cause of secondary hypertension (5-10% of hypertensives, 20% of RESISTANT hypertension). Autonomous aldosterone excess drives hypertension through FOUR pathway targets: (1) RENAL SODIUM RETENTION: MR activation in collecting duct principal cells → Aldosterone binds cytoplasmic MR → MR-aldosterone translocates to nucleus → increases transcription of: (a) ENaC (epithelial sodium channel) — apical Na⁺ reabsorption, (b) Na/K-ATPase — basolateral Na⁺ extrusion, (c) SGK1 (serum/glucocorticoid-regulated kinase 1) — stabilizes ENaC on apical membrane. Net effect: massive sodium reabsorption → volume expansion → hypertension. Potassium is secreted in exchange via ROMK channels → HYPOKALEMIA (present in ~50% but absence does NOT exclude PA). (2) VASCULAR DAMAGE: MR on vascular smooth muscle → NADPH oxidase activation → ROS (reactive oxygen species) → oxidative stress → NO scavenging → endothelial dysfunction → vasoconstriction + vascular fibrosis. Aldosterone also upregulates AT1 receptors → enhances angiotensin II signaling → additional vasoconstriction. (3) CARDIAC REMODELING: Cardiac MR activation → collagen deposition → myocardial FIBROSIS → LVH out of proportion to blood pressure level → diastolic dysfunction → HFpEF. Studies show 2-4× more LVH in PA patients compared to essential hypertension at the same BP level. (4) CENTRAL SYMPATHETIC ACTIVATION: Aldosterone in the brain (crosses BBB) → activates MR in the rostral ventrolateral medulla (RVLM) and nucleus tractus solitarius → increases sympathetic outflow → vasoconstriction + cardiac stimulation → hypertension. WHY CONVENTIONAL DRUGS FAIL: ACE-I/ARB → block RAAS but aldosterone ESCAPES (autonomous production not dependent on angiotensin II). CCB → vasodilate but don't address sodium retention or fibrosis. Thiazide → produces natriuresis but can worsen hypokalemia and doesn't block MR-mediated vascular/cardiac damage. SPIRONOLACTONE: Blocks MR at ALL anatomical sites → (1) Renal: natriuresis + potassium retention, (2) Vascular: reduced oxidative stress + restored NO → vasodilation, (3) Cardiac: reduced fibrosis + regression of LVH, (4) CNS: reduced sympathetic outflow. PATHWAY-4 trial: Spironolactone was the MOST effective add-on for resistant hypertension (mean BP reduction ~8/4 mmHg beyond existing triple therapy).",
