    explanationB: "Spironolactone blocks the MINERALOCORTICOID RECEPTOR on target tissues — it does NOT block cortisol receptors in the adrenal gland or suppress aldosterone production. Aldosterone production continues but its effects are blocked at the receptor level. (Cross-reactivity with androgen/progesterone receptors → gynecomastia/breast tenderness side effects.)",
    explanationC: "Primary aldosteronism is NOT benign — PA patients have significantly higher cardiovascular event rates (stroke, MI, AF, HF) than essential hypertensives at the SAME BP level, due to aldosterone's direct tissue damage. Spironolactone is specifically indicated to address this pathophysiology.",
    explanationD: "Correct. Aldosterone drives resistant hypertension through FOUR mechanistic axes: renal (sodium retention), vascular (oxidative stress/fibrosis), cardiac (fibrosis/LVH), and CNS (sympathetic activation). Spironolactone addresses ALL by blocking MR at every site — a root-cause, not symptomatic, treatment.",
    examTip: "Primary aldosteronism workup: Screen with ARR (aldosterone/renin ratio >30 is suspicious). Confirm: saline infusion test, oral sodium loading, or fludrocortisone suppression. Subtype: CT adrenals + adrenal vein sampling. Unilateral adenoma → laparoscopic adrenalectomy (CURATIVE). Bilateral hyperplasia → lifelong spironolactone or eplerenone. Eplerenone: more selective MR antagonist → less gynecomastia/sexual side effects (no androgen/progesterone cross-reactivity) but weaker and more expensive.",
