    rationale: "PRINZMETAL (VARIANT) ANGINA PATHOPHYSIOLOGY: Transient epicardial coronary artery spasm → complete or near-complete occlusion → transmural ischemia → ST ELEVATION (unlike demand-mediated stable angina which causes subendocardial ischemia → ST depression). Occurs predominantly at REST, often 2-5 AM (circadian variation in coronary vasomotor tone — highest parasympathetic/lowest sympathetic activity). May occur in atherosclerotic OR angiographically normal coronary arteries. SPASM MECHANISM: (1) Endothelial dysfunction → reduced NO production → lost vasodilatory protection. (2) Smooth muscle hyperreactivity to constrictive stimuli: acetylcholine (normally causes endothelium-dependent vasodilation via NO → in dysfunctional endothelium, ACh directly constricts smooth muscle via M3 muscarinic receptors). (3) Rho-kinase activation → enhanced myosin light chain phosphorylation → sustained contraction. (4) Provocative factors: smoking (endothelial damage), cocaine (sympathomimetic vasospasm), cold exposure, hyperventilation (respiratory alkalosis → vasoconstriction). TREATMENT: (1) CALCIUM CHANNEL BLOCKERS (first-line): Amlodipine, nifedipine, diltiazem → block L-type Ca²⁺ channels on coronary smooth muscle → prevent calcium entry → prevent vasospasm. High prophylactic efficacy (>90% symptom reduction). (2) NITRATES: Sublingual NTG for acute attacks → NO → sGC → cGMP → smooth muscle relaxation → rapid spasm relief. Long-acting nitrates (isosorbide mononitrate) for prophylaxis (with nitrate-free interval). (3) AVOID BETA-BLOCKERS: β2 receptors on coronary smooth muscle → vasodilation. Beta-blocker β2 blockade → removes this vasodilatory influence → tips the balance toward alpha-1-mediated coronary vasoconstriction → can PRECIPITATE or WORSEN vasospasm → recurrent angina, potential MI. Severely harmful: non-selective beta-blockers (propranolol, carvedilol) > cardioselective (metoprolol, bisoprolol — less harmful but still not recommended).",
    explanationA: "Prinzmetal angina is caused by VASOSPASM, not fixed stenosis. It has transient ST ELEVATION (not depression), occurs at REST (not exertion), and responds to vasodilators (not beta-blockers). It is pathophysiologically distinct from typical angina.",
    explanationB: "Correct. Coronary vasospasm → transmural ischemia → ST elevation. CCBs prevent spasm (prophylactic), NTG reverses acute spasm. Beta-blockers remove β2-mediated coronary vasodilation → unopposed alpha-1 constriction → worsened spasm.",
    explanationC: "Prinzmetal angina is a well-documented cardiovascular condition with objective findings (ST elevation on ECG, provokable on catheterization with acetylcholine/ergonovine). It is not psychiatric and can cause MI, ventricular arrhythmias, and sudden death.",
    explanationD: "Beta-blockers are contraindicated because of their effect on coronary vascular TONE (removing β2 vasodilation), not coronary calcification. Calcium channel blockers prevent smooth muscle contraction, not arterial calcification.",
    examTip: "Vasospastic angina triggers: smoking (MOST important modifiable risk), cocaine, triptans (5-HT1B receptor → coronary vasoconstriction — contraindicated in variant angina), cold exposure, hyperventilation. Diagnosis: ST elevation during chest pain that resolves with NTG, or provocative testing (IV acetylcholine or ergonovine during catheterization → spasm provoked → diagnostic). Complications: ventricular arrhythmias during spasm (VT/VF), MI from prolonged spasm, sudden cardiac death. Unlike atherosclerotic CAD, more common in young women and smokers.",
